image.latex-image:
\begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.72, >=stealth]
    \draw[->] (-6.2,0) -- (6.7,0) node[right] {\(x\)};
    \draw[->] (0,-6.2) -- (0,6.7) node[above] {\(y\)};

    \draw[gray!25, step=1] (-6,-6) grid (6,6);
    \draw[thick] (0,0) circle (5);

    \fill (3,4) circle (2.5pt);
    \node[above right] at (3,4) {\((3,4)\)};

    \fill (-3,-4) circle (2.5pt);
    \node[below left] at (-3,-4) {\((-3,-4)\)};

    \draw[->, very thick, blue!60!black] (3,4) -- ++(1.2,1.6)
        node[above right] {\(\nabla g\)};
    \draw[->, very thick, red!65!black] (3,4) -- ++(1.8,2.4)
        node[right] {\(\nabla S\)};

    \draw[->, very thick, blue!60!black] (-3,-4) -- ++(-1.2,-1.6)
        node[below left] {\(\nabla g\)};
    \draw[->, very thick, red!65!black] (-3,-4) -- ++(1.8,2.4)
        node[right] {\(\nabla S\)};

    \node at (0,-7.0) {At a constrained extremum, \(\nabla S\) is parallel to the constraint normal.};
\end{tikzpicture}

subsection.p:
In differential-form language, the same idea is even shorter. Allowed tangent vectors \mathbf v satisfy dg(\mathbf v)=0. At a constrained extremum, df(\mathbf v)=0 for every allowed tangent vector. If dg
e0, the two 1-forms have the same kernel, so  oxed{df=\lambda\,dg.} In coordinates, this is  oxed{
abla f=\lambda
abla g.}

statement.p:
Then there is a number \lambda such that
\boxed{\nabla f(\mathbf p)=\lambda\nabla g(\mathbf p).}
Equivalently,
\boxed{df_{\mathbf p}=\lambda\,dg_{\mathbf p}.}

subsection.p:
At a constrained extremum, 
abla f must also be perpendicular to the allowed tangent direction. Therefore 
abla f must lie in the plane spanned by the two constraint gradients:  oxed{
abla f=\lambda
abla g+\mu
abla h.}

statement.p:
Then there are numbers \lambda and \mu such that
\boxed{\nabla f(\mathbf p)=\lambda\nabla g(\mathbf p)+\mu\nabla h(\mathbf p).}
Equivalently,
\boxed{df_{\mathbf p}=\lambda\,dg_{\mathbf p}+\mu\,dh_{\mathbf p}.}
